An employer may terminate an employment for one of several just causes listed under Article 297(2)(a)-(e):  
(a) Serious misconduct or willful disobedience;
(b) Gross and habitual neglect of duties;
(c) Fraud or willful breach of trust;
(d) Commission of a crime or offense against the person of the employer or close relatives;
(e) Causes analogous to those mentioned above.

An unfair labor practice by employers according to Section A of Art. 259(248), specifically:

(a) Interferes with, restrains or coerces employees in exercising their right to self-
organization;
(b) Requires that a person or an employee will not join a labor organization or must leave one if already joined;
(c) Contracts out services/functions currently done by union members knowing it would affect their ability to organize themselves;
(d) Initiates, dominates, assists interference with forming/administering a labor organization through funding/support given directly/indirectly;
(e) Discriminates regarding wage/hour/terms & conditions of employment based on joining/not joining a labor group.

Wage deductions can be prohibited if they do not fall within certain exceptions outlined in Article 113:

(a) When workers have agreed to insurance premiums deducted;
(b) Union dues collected through written authorization from each member;
(c) Lawfully mandated deductions approved by the Secretary of Labor and Employment.
